**Clinical Reasoning:**
In retrospective studies where individuals recall past behaviors such as prenatal supplement use, memory inaccuracies or biases in reporting can occur — especially if those with healthier outcomes (like no ASD) might remember taking supplements better than those with negative outcomes. This leads to overestimation of exposure in cases without disease, introducing **recall bias**, which could distort observed associations.

